  "prompt": "Which one is grammatically correct: pick up someone at the airport or from the airport?",
  "response": "Both phrases\u2014**\"pick up someone at the airport\"** and **\"pick up someone from the airport\"**\u2014are grammatically correct and commonly used in English. While they can often be used interchangeably, there are subtle nuances between the two:\n\n1. **Pick up someone at the airport:**\n   - **Focus:** Emphasizes the *location* where the pickup will occur.\n   - **Usage Example:** \"I'll pick you up at the airport around 3 PM.\"\n\n2. **Pick up someone from the airport:**\n   - **Focus:** Emphasizes the *origin* of the person being picked up.\n   - **Usage Example:** \"She's coming to pick me up from the airport after my flight.\"\n\n**Which One to Use?**\n- **Interchangeably:** In most contexts, either phrase works fine without causing confusion.\n- **Contextual Preference:** You might choose one over the other based on what you want to emphasize (the location vs. the origin).\n\n**Additional Examples:**\n- \"They will pick their friends up **at** the airport.\"\n- \"He needs to pick his sister up **from** the airport before midnight.\"\n\nIn summary, both expressions are correct. Your choice can depend on which aspect you want to highlight, but using either will be understood clearly by native speakers.",
